    <title type="text">QuarryScapes Atlas</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas_text.php">QuarryScapes
      Atlas</a><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><img
      alt="http://www.quarryscapes.no/bannere/banner1.jpg" class="decoded" height="60"
      src="http://www.quarryscapes.no/bannere/banner1.jpg" width="320" />
      </blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size: x-small;">The
      QuarryScapes Atlas displays a variety of ancient quarry landscapes. The purpose of the atlas is
      first of all to show the great variability of such landscapes and introducing them with photos
      and few words. The atlas will be further developed, and hopefully evolve to a comprehensive
      web-book with contributions from many researchers. In this first edition of the atlas we have
      picked 15 quarry landscapes; most of them in the project region, but also a few outside.
      Collectively, these 15 sites display a broad range of quarry landscapes; different periods and
      historical settings, different geology, morphology and climate. Also, they are in different
      stages of development as cultural heritage sites, from “unknown and remote” to outdoor museums.
      </span></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">Click the links below to download sheets from the atlas. Or, take the trip to
      visit them via Google Earth by following the link below. Please note that some of the most
      vulnerable quarry landscapes below are deliberately not displayed via the Google Earth
      Link.&nbsp; </span></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">A printed version of the Atlas can also be ordered at <a
      href="mailto:Biblioteket@ngu.no">Biblioteket@ngu.no</a>. For comments or suggestions,
      please contact <a href="mailto:tom.heldal@ngu.no">tom.heldal@ngu.no</a>.&nbsp;
      </span></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><b><span style="font-weight: normal;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/quarryscapes%20atlas.kmz">Take the trip on Google
      Earth</a></span></b> (if it does not work by selecting "open", try save to
      disk and then "open with" google earth. If you don't have google earth installed, download from
      <a href="http://earth.google.com/">this
      link</a>)</span></blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">Download single sheets:</span><br
      /><ul><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/aliki.pdf">Aliki, Thassos,
      Greece</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/aswan_granite.pdf">Aswan Unifinished Obelisk quarry,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/aswan_westbank.pdf">Aswan West Bank,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/bibemus.pdf">Bibemus,
      France</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/chephrens_quarry.pdf">Chephren’s Quarry,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/silsila.pdf">Gebel el-Silsila,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/hyllestad.pdf">Hyllestad,
      Norway</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/jerash.pdf">Jerash,
      Jordan</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/karystos.pdf">Karystos,
      Greece</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/mons_claudianus.pdf">Mons Claudianus,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/petra.pdf">Petra,
      Jordan</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/rod_el_baram.pdf">Rod el-Baram,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/sagalassos.pdf">Sagalassos,
      Turkey</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/umm_essawan.pdf">Umm es-Sawan,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/widan.pdf">Widan el-Faras,
      Egypt</a></span></li><li><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.quarryscapes.no/atlas/QS_del13_atlas.pdf">All quarry landscapes
      </a>(Report version, A4 reduced size)
      </span></li></ul></blockquote><div style="text-align:
      center;"><span style="font-family: inherit;"><span style="font-size:
      small;"><span style="font-weight: normal;">And see AWOL'S <a
      href="http://ancientworldonline.blogspot.com/2012/09/roundup-of-resources-on-ancient.html">Roundup
      of Resources on Ancient
      Geography</a></span></span></span></div>]]></content>
